The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \( E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda} \), where \( N_A \) is Avogadro's number (\( 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1} \)), \( h \) is Planck's constant (\( 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \)), \( c \) is the speed of light (\( 3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \)), and \( \lambda \) is the wavelength in meters. The wavelength is given as \( 300 \, \text{nm} \), which is \( 300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} \).

First, calculate the energy per photon:  
\[ E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{hc}{\lambda} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \]

Then, calculate the energy per mole:  
\[ E_{\text{mol}} = E_{\text{photon}} \times N_A = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol} \]

Convert to kJ/mol (1 kJ = 1000 J):  
\[ E_{\text{mol}} = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399.0 \, \text{kJ/mol} \]

Rounding to three significant figures (based on the given wavelength of 300 nm and constants), the energy is \( 399 \, \text{kJ/mol} \).

