Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds 8 after 10 triples, with each drug having a success probability of 0.7 per administration.

Since \(p_1 = p_2 = p_3 = 0.7\), and each drug is administered 10 times (once per triple for 10 triples), the number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution: \(S_i \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\) for \(i = 1, 2, 3\).

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds 8 is \(P(\max\{S_1, S_2, S_3\} > 8)\). This is equivalent to \(1 - P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8)\).

First, compute \(P(S \leq 8)\) for one drug, where \(S \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\):
- \(P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10)\)
- \(P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3 = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S > 8) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)
- \(P(S \leq 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\)

Since the \(S_i\) are independent and identically distributed:
- \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = [P(S \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3 = 0.6156253804\)

Then:
- \(P(\max S_i > 8) = 1 - 0.6156253804 = 0.3843746196\)

Rounded to three significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

